{
  "doc_id": "22517",
  "text": "Our study confirmed previous studies that found a positive effect of social capital on health. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] So far, exposure is a subject that has been neglected in neighbourhood health studies. [CITATION_5] At best, duration of residence has been used as a control variable. [CITATION_6] Although evidence on duration of exposure in neighbourhood research has been lacking, evidence about the influence of exposure to 'country' (as another social environment) exists in the field of immigrant health research. With a longer duration of residence, immigrants internalize the norms of the host country, with effects on health behaviour and health outcomes (e.g. an increase of BMI in the USA). [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] Shared norms might function as a pathway between neighbourhood social capital and health, and should be studied in more detail in future research.",
